Thought for 11 seconds
To build a 100% sovereign, air-gapped, unrestricted AI agent factory at maximum speed, you cannot build everything manually. The secret is to bootstrap: you first deploy a single "Master Co-Partner" coding agent, and then you command that agent to write the code, configure the frameworks, and deploy the rest of the factory.

Here is the fastest, most cutting-edge technical blueprint to deploy this infrastructure offline.

Phase 1: The Sovereign Infrastructure (The Metal & Brain)
To run advanced agentic workflows locally without cloud APIs, you need VRAM (Video RAM).

Hardware Requirement: At minimum, a Mac Studio (M2/M3 Ultra with 128GB+ Unified Memory) OR a PC rig with 2x to 4x RTX 3090/4090s (48GB–96GB VRAM).
The OS: Ubuntu Linux or macOS (better for Docker and local AI orchestration).
Step 1: Install the Inference Engine (Ollama / vLLM)
Ollama is the fastest way to serve local models with an OpenAI-compatible API that your agents will need.

Download Ollama on an internet-connected machine, transfer to your air-gapped machine, and install.
Pull your foundational models (do this before air-gapping):
ollama run qwen2.5-coder:32b (Your primary, unrestricted coding brain—currently the best open-weight coder).
ollama run deepseek-r1:70b or llama-3.3-70b (For high-level logic, reasoning, and manager roles).
Phase 2: Deploying the "Master Co-Partner" Agent
This is your Manus/ChatGPT-4o/Copilot equivalent. It sits in your IDE or terminal, takes your natural language commands, and executes code directly on your local machine.

The Fastest Tool: Cline (formerly Claude Dev) + VS Code

Install VS Code (or VSCodium for full telemetry-free sovereignty).
Install the Cline extension (an autonomous coding agent that lives in your editor).
Configure Cline for Local:
Go to Cline settings.
Set API Provider to OpenAI Compatible.
Set Base URL to http://localhost:11434/v1 (Ollama's local port).
Set Model to qwen2.5-coder:32b.
Alternative for Full Autonomy: Deploy OpenHands (formerly OpenDevin) via Docker. OpenHands is a fully autonomous agent running in a sandbox that can browse local files, use the terminal, and write code based on your chat commands.
Phase 3: Commanding the Co-Partner to Build the "Factory"
Now that you have your Co-Partner coder running locally, you stop coding. You now manage. You will prompt your Co-Partner to build the Agent Factory.

Prompt your Co-Partner (in Cline/OpenHands):

"I want to build a local AI agent studio using Python. Initialize a new project. Install crewai, langchain, and langgraph. Create a modular framework where I can define different 'Ops Divisions' (e.g., Research, QA, Development). Configure all LLM calls to route to http://localhost:11434/v1 using Langchain's OpenAI wrapper."

The Co-Partner will autonomously write the scripts, set up the virtual environments, and create the directory structure for your workforce.

Phase 4: Deploying the Factory Studio UI
You need a central dashboard to visualize your agent workflows, manage their memory (RAG), and deploy them.

Command your Co-Partner:

"Write a Docker Compose file to deploy locally: 1) Dify.ai (or Flowise) for our Agent Studio UI. 2) Qdrant or ChromaDB for our local vector database (memory). 3) PostgreSQL for logging agent actions. Ensure all run entirely offline."

Dify.ai / Flowise: These are open-source, visual node-based frameworks. Once your Co-Partner deploys them, you can open localhost:3000 in your browser.
You now have a drag-and-drop studio where you can visually link your local models to specific tools (local web search, file parsing, code execution).
Phase 5: Creating Ops Divisions & Sub-Agents
With the infrastructure up, you use your Studio UI (or Python scripts managed by your Co-Partner) to spin up specific divisions.

Example Setup (The "Software Dev" Division):
Using CrewAI (which your master agent configured in Phase 3), you create a crew:

Agent 1: Senior Architect (Model: DeepSeek-R1:70b). Role: Breaks down your natural language request into a technical blueprint.
Agent 2: Senior Programmer (Model: Qwen2.5-Coder:32b). Role: Writes the actual code based on the blueprint.
Agent 3: QA Tester (Model: Qwen2.5-Coder:32b). Role: Reviews the code, runs it in a local Python sandbox, and reports errors back to the Programmer.
Summary of the Fastest Workflow
Metal: Boot massive RAM machine.
Brain: curl -fsSL https://ollama.com/install.sh | sh -> ollama run qwen2.5-coder:32b.
Master Builder: Open VS Code -> Install Cline -> Point to localhost:11434.
Disconnect: Pull internet plug. You are now 100% sovereign.
Construct: Tell Cline: "Build a multi-agent framework using CrewAI, a vector database using Chroma, and a UI using Streamlit. Route all intelligence to my local Ollama endpoint."
By using an existing open-source agent UI (Cline/OpenHands) connected to a local top-tier coding model, you bypass months of manual setup. The AI builds its own house.

how can i simplify and minimize human involvement aka have ai agents build/set up this/ these inital steps

Thought for 8 seconds
Because you didn't specify exactly what you are trying to build or set up in your prompt, I will give you a universal blueprint for how to use autonomous AI agents to handle the initial setup of almost any project—whether it's a software codebase, a business automation workflow, a cloud infrastructure, or a marketing campaign.

To minimize human involvement to near zero, you need to move away from using AI as a "chatbot" and start using Agentic Orchestration—where AI agents have tools, roles, and the ability to execute actions on your behalf.

Here is how you can set up AI agents to autonomously build your initial steps:

1. Choose the Right Agent Framework
Depending on what you are building, you need a framework that allows agents to talk to each other and execute tasks.

For Software Development & System Setup: Use Microsoft AutoGen or CrewAI. These allow you to create a "team" of agents (e.g., a Project Manager agent, a Developer agent, and a QA agent). You give the Manager the goal, and it delegates the setup tasks to the others.
For Business/Workflow Automations: Use n8n, Zapier Central, or Make.com. These allow you to drag and drop AI agents into workflows where they can autonomously interact with hundreds of apps (Slack, Gmail, CRMs, databases) without you coding.
For App/Code scaffolding: Use Cursor (an AI IDE), Devin (or open-source alternatives like OpenDevin / SWE-agent). You give them a prompt, and they will write the code, install dependencies, configure the servers, and test the app.
2. The "Zero-Human" Blueprint
To have agents do the setup for you, you must follow this specific workflow:

Step 1: Create the "Master Spec" (Your only major human task)
Agents need extreme clarity to work without you. Instead of doing the setup yourself, write a highly detailed "Requirements Document."

What to include: The final goal, the specific tools to be used, API keys/credentials they will need, and exactly what constitutes "success."
Tip: You can actually ask ChatGPT or Claude to write this Master Spec for you based on a rough 3-sentence idea.
Step 2: Equip Agents with "Tools" (Access)
An AI agent can't set up a server or create a database if it doesn't have hands. You must give your agents tools:

Terminal/CLI Access: Allow the agent to run terminal commands to install packages, create directories, or start environments.
API Keys: Give the agent access to your AWS, GitHub, Stripe, CRM, or whichever platforms are required for the setup.
File Read/Write Access: Allow them to create and modify files on your system.
Step 3: Use an "Orchestrator Agent"
Never assign a massive task to one agent. Set up an Orchestrator (Manager) Agent.

You feed the Master Spec to the Orchestrator.
The Orchestrator breaks the setup down into 10 smaller steps.
It spawns "Sub-Agents" (e.g., a Setup Agent, an API configuration Agent) to do each micro-task.
The Orchestrator checks their work and only reports back to you when it's completely done.
Step 4: Implement a "Human-in-the-Loop" (HITL) Fallback
While you want minimal involvement, you don't want agents running wild with your credit card or production databases. Frameworks like LangGraph and CrewAI allow you to set an "Approval Node." The AI will do 99% of the work (writing the code, configuring the tool) and then simply ping you saying: "I am about to deploy this setup. Do you approve? (Y/N)."

How to get started right now
